  "summary": "This chunk provides detailed analysis of magic circles in the Munich Handbook (CLM 849), including their structure, inscriptions (spirit names, sacred phrases), and layout. It lists numerous named spirits—especially demons like Belial, Astaroth, Satan, Lucifer, Berith—and describes how they appear in circle diagrams with positional instructions for magicians and mediums. Sacred names (Agla, Tetragrammaton, Alpha et O) are used alongside spirit names to enhance efficacy. Ritual tools include circles inscribed on ground or vellum, pentagrams, swords, candles, and censers; ingredients include verbena and cemetery stones.",
  "key_passages": [
    "The circle for no. 12 gives a modified conjuration [...] Tu Belial, tu Astaroth, tu Paymon, ad hoc sitis opus michi adiutores.",
    "No. 1 has the names of the spirits Belial, Satan, Osendior, Matalot, Belzebub, Lucifer, Sententino and Apolin inscribed in and around its band.",
    "The position of the master is often marked in the centre of the circle, with the term Locus magistri [...] No. 22 [...] Hie sederat puer super signum (at the top), and Hie sedeat magister super signum a latere sinistro (at the bottom).",
    "Inscriptions are of various kinds: 1. Four cardinal directions, with east on top [...]; 2. Positions of the master and child medium [...]; 3. Names of spirits, given most frequently within the bands.",
    "No. 40 has [...] ft* Hunc circulum facio in nomine Patris omnipotentis dei, qui solo verbo cuncta creauit."
  ]
}